Krispy Kreme is accelerating its transition to capital-light growth through refranchising as part of its turnaround plan announced in August. The company announced a transaction with franchisee WKS Restaurant Group to increase WKS’ ownership stake in a joint venture agreement between it and Krispy Kreme from 45% to 80%, while also expanding its footprint.&nbsp;

As part of the deal, announced Tuesday, WKS added 23 shops in California and Hawaii that were previously company-owned, adding to its existing 50-shop footprint and about 1,000 “Delivered Fresh Daily” locations with partners including Kroger, Target, and Walmart. The joint venture also plans to develop additional shops and grow the DFD model in coming years.

The main objective of Krispy Kreme's turnaround plan is to reduce debt and drive profitable growth through refranchising. The transaction provides the company with approximately $90 million, including $50 million cash at closing.&nbsp;

“Our long-standing partnership with WKS has been key to Krispy Kreme’s growth in the Western U.S. This transaction advances our strategy to drive sustainable, profitable growth through capital-light refranchising while further reducing our leverage,” Krispy Kreme chief executive officer Josh Charlesworth said in a statement.&nbsp;

WKS president and CEO Roland Spongberg said the company is reinforcing its confidence in Krispy Kreme by increasing its ownership stake and “positioning the business to accelerate development across the Western U.S.”&nbsp;

WKS Restaurant Group was founded by Roland Spongberg in 1987 and has since grown to become a franchisee of four brands — Wendy’s, Denny’s, El Pollo Loco, and Krispy Kreme — operating in 19 states. WKS Restaurant Group currently represents about 15% of Krispy Kreme’s U.S. revenues.&nbsp;

Unison Capital transaction closes&nbsp;

Krispy Kreme also completed its previously announced agreement with Unison Capital to refranchise operations in Japan. Cash proceeds from this transaction were nearly $70 million and were used to pay down debt, after transaction-related fees and expenses. Krispy Kreme is targeting two to three international refranchising deals this year.

During Krispy Kreme’s fourth quarter earnings call in late February, Charlesworth said the company expects nearly 50% of systemwide sales to come from franchisees by the beginning of 2027.&nbsp;

